1. Define the waves
Create a list of waves.

Each wave has a number of enemies and a spawn rate.

Example: Wave 1 spawns 5 enemies, one every second.

ğŸ“ 2. Check if a player is nearby
Before spawning, check if any player is close to the spawn point.

Only spawn enemies if a player is within a certain radius (e.g. 100 studs).

This prevents enemies from spawning when no one is around.

ğŸ§ 3. Spawn enemies
Clone an enemy model from storage.

Place it at the spawn location.

Repeat this for the number of enemies in the wave.

ğŸ’€ 4. Track enemy deaths
When an enemy dies, decrease the â€œenemies aliveâ€ counter.

This helps you know when the wave is finished.

â³ 5. Wait until all enemies are dead
After spawning all enemies, wait until the alive counter reaches zero.

This means the wave is complete.

ğŸ•’ 6. Intermission
Wait a few seconds before starting the next wave.

You can show a countdown or message to players.

ğŸ” 7. Repeat for the next wave
Move to the next wave in the list.

Repeat the same steps: check player, spawn, track deaths, wait, intermission.